communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI: Jack Hoover Aldrich
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All Bureau records that might exist that mention or pertain to my grandfather Jack Hoover Aldrich (born 8-17-1920 - died 4-1-2014). Attached is his obituary. 

https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/127474305/jack-hoover-aldrich

My grandfather worked for American Car and Foundry (ACF Industries) in the state of New Mexico in the 1950s. According to my mother's recollection, my grandfather had to undergo a federal background check as his employment involved the transport of nuclear weapon materials by train car by the ACF corporation. My mother recalls federal law enforcement interviewing neighbors and friends in 1956, and then periodic checks afterwards. My grandfather also made repeated trips to the Philippines, where he met Imelda Marcos and other officials in the Philippine government. I am curious as to whether the bureau maintained a file on my grandfather. 

This request is for any and all records about my grandfather Jack Hoover Aldrich from any and all FBI offices, including HQ, field offices, legal attaches, and facilities that maintain records under the FBI’s control. Please conduct a search for any records on Aldrich held by the Albuquerque Field Office. According to a blog post I just read, it is important that I state the following: "As you know, your agency is required to search the records stored at NARA’s Washington Records Center in Suitland, MD, but still technically under your agency’s control. For more information see 36 CFR 1250.8" Please also conduct a physical search of records at NARA's Washington Records Center in Suitland, for any records or documents related to Aldrich.

Please include all potentially responsive materials, including but not limited to all communications, reports, inquiries, investigations, photographs, audio files, video files, memos, directives, etc. Please include all materials found in other subject files and all materials associated with any potentially-related names and any other known aliases, nicknames, code names, or any other identifying pseudonyms or references utilized by this agency. Please consult the Central Records System and records, the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Data Management System and records, Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) records, Physical Surveillance (FISUR) records, Technical Surveillance (TESUR) records, and all available cross-reference indices, databases, and records, in addition to any other locations containing potentially-responsive materials related to Jack Hoover Aldrich.

Please include a search of any records or documents understood to be, or colloquially referred to as "COINTELPRO records" under the bureau's custody that could be construed as responsive to a request for records related to Jack Hoover Aldrich.

If the bureau cannot fulfill certain parts of this request or if certain portions must be redacted, please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Reports show that USACE has been in contact with Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, son of Gov. Pedro Pierluisi Urrutia and owner of Silver Beach LLC, about a pier located within or near the boundaries of a property owned by Stay West Indied called "Mary Lee's by the Sea" in Guanica, Puerto Rico. The same reports show that their exists no  "maintenance permit" or a "nationwide permit" for the pier:

https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/gobierno/notas/hijo-del-gobernador-se-defiende-ante-falta-de-permisos-en-guanica-el-muelle-esta-fuera-de-la-propiedad/
https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/gobierno/notas/anthony-pierluisi-rojo-colaborara-con-investigaciones-sobre-supuestas-violaciones-ambientales-en-sus-propiedades/

Therefore, I request the following records:

1) Any communications, emails, text messages, and attachments exchanged between USACE and Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, employees of Silver Beach, LLC, and employees of Stay West Indies, the short-term rental company which Pierluisi is the general manager for, concerning properties owned or operated by Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC, and Stay West Indies

2) Any records concerning permits or the lack thereof of properties owned or operated by Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indies. Any records concerning permits or the lack thereof of piers located in or near properties owned or operated by either Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indie.

3) Any records about an investigation into the lack of permits for properties owned or operated by either Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indies. Any records concerning investigation into the lack of permits of piers located in or near properties owned or operated by either Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indie.

4) Any communications, emails, text messages, and attachments between USACE and Puerto Rico Department of Natural and Environmental Resources (DRNA, by their Spanish acronym) concerning Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC, and Stay West Indies.

Keywords: "Anthony Pierluisi," "Pierluisi Rojo," "Pierluisi," "DRNA," "Stay West Indies," "Silver Beach,  LLC," "Silver Beach,"  "Guanica," "Mary Lee's by the Sea," "Mary Lee's."

To help aid in your search, I believe that employees of Stay West Indies' email addresses end with "@staywestindies.com"

This records request is for records between January 1, 2020 and the time this request is processed.  

This record is not being made for commercial purposes. I am a freelance journalist and records retrieved from this request will be used in the course of reporting about Puerto Rico's beaches and the archipelago's permits office.

Steffani Lon

title: May 1, 2023 "Explosive Artifact" at LUMA Office in Puerto Rico (Federal Bureau of Investigation)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Reports show that there was an "explosive artifact" found near the offices of LUMA Energy in Guayama, Puerto Rico on May 1, 2023: https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/seguridad/notas/policia-desactiva-artefacto-explosivo-encontrado-en-las-inmediaciones-de-las-oficinas-de-luma-energy-en-guayama/

Joseph González, director of the FBI for Puerto Rico and USVI, spoke with local Puerto Rican newspapers about whether the item was a real bomb or not: https://www.metro.pr/noticias/2023/05/03/fbi-no-confirma-si-artefacto-encontrado-en-luma-era-una-bomba/

Additionally, through my own reporting, I confirmed with the Puerto Rico Police Department that the artifacts and documents related to it were handed over to the FBI on or around May 2, 2023.

Therefore, I request the following records:

1) Any communications, emails, text messages, and attachments concerning an item resembling the artifact found near the offices of LUMA Energy in Guayama, Puerto Rico on May 1, 2023. Please included any communications and attachments between FBI personnel, as well as those exchanged with local Puerto Rican agencies, such as the Puerto Rico Police Department or the Municipality of Guayama.

2) Any after action reports or documentation created in response to the aforementioned incident. These should include but are not limited to write ups, executive summaries, and complaints.

3) Any pictures or videos produced in response to the aforementioned incident.

This request is for all records produced from April 30, 2023 to the date this request is processed.

This request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am a Puerto Rican journalist and all responsive records will be used in the course of reporting about May Day actions in Puerto Rico.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Carlos Berríos Polanco

Dear Emma Parry, 
 
 PAYMENT DUE 
 
The City may be the custodian of at least some of the requested public records and a payment is due to continue processing this request. Please log into the Portland Public Records Request Center to pay these fees. 
 
Fees include research time to locate and analyze the requested records, even if no records are located or if the requested records are determined to be exempt from disclosure. We will not be working on your request until we receive the payment. 
 
Please log in to the Portland Public Records Request Center (copy and right click this link to open it in your browser) and make a payment on this request. 
 
You may pay by electronic check or credit card by going to "My Public Records Request Center" and select "View My Invoices." Then scroll to find your open invoice and select "Make Payment." Follow the screen prompts to make a payment. 
 
Due to the current state of emergency, most City offices are not staffed. Consequently, if you mail a check it could delay the response time and it is preferable that you use the online payment portal to make an electronic payment. However, if you need to mail a check, please reply to this message and ask for the correct address. Please be sure and provide your Reference Number (S338192-050124) on your check. 
 
Please be advised that pursuant to ORS 192.329(3)(b) and (4)(b), your public records request will be closed if payment is not received within sixty (60) days of this invoice. 
 
 
Sincerely, 
 
 
City of Portland Public Records Responder
